    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my civil eng midterm and im a bit stuck on materials. why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside concrete foundations? like i get that concrete is strong, but why does the steel part matter so much for the actual structure? i'm specifically confused about the difference between compressive and tensile strength in this context.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is incredibly strong in resisting **compression**—being squeezed—but it is quite weak when being pulled apart, which is called **tension**. Steel rebar is specifically used to counteract these tensile forces because steel has very high tensile strength. By embedding the steel within the concrete, the composite material allows the entire foundation to efficiently handle both pushing (compression) and pulling (tension) forces simultaneously. This synergy results in a much stronger and more durable structure than either material could achieve alone.",
      "source": "target",
