    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically concrete handles the weight pushing down on it, and the rebar handles the tension? i was reading something about how if you don't have enough steel, the concrete might develop micro-cracks internally even if it looks solid on the outside. is there a specific way the steel prevents those internal cracks from spreading through the whole slab?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that's the core concept: concrete handles the crushing loads, and the rebar manages the stretching or pulling forces. The steel acts like a network of internal tension straps that arrest the growth of micro-cracks as soon as they begin to form due to stress or shrinkage. Even small cracks can propagate and lead to catastrophic failure if left unchecked, so the reinforcing steel carries the load across these incipient cracks. Essentially, it provides distributed tensile resistance across the entire tension zone, preventing minor flaws from becoming major structural defects.",
      "source": "target",
